{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658173"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:43:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:43:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20715"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20715"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.09,0,0.64,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13591"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96908"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13591"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79523"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11587"},{"type":"tags","id":"11762"},{"type":"tags","id":"12594"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32681"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96908"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA thrombus can undergo several different processes after its initial formation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the natural evolution of an established thrombus that remains in situ?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate embolisation to distant sites","Complete dissolution through fibrinolysis","Conversion to adipose tissue","Organisation with recanalisation","Calcification without remodelling"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen a thrombus remains in place, \u003Cstrong\u003Eorganisation with recanalisation\u003C/strong\u003E occurs through the ingrowth of endothelial cells, smooth muscle cells, and fibroblasts. These cells form new capillary channels that help restore blood flow through the affected vessel. The thrombus gradually becomes incorporated into the vessel wall as fibrous tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate embolisation to distant sites\u003C/strong\u003E - While embolisation can occur, it is not the typical fate of stable thrombi that remain in place\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete dissolution through fibrinolysis\u003C/strong\u003E - While recent thrombi may dissolve through fibrinolysis, older established thrombi typically undergo organisation instead\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion to adipose tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - Thrombi are replaced by fibrous tissue, not adipose tissue\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcification without remodelling\u003C/strong\u003E - While calcification can occur in chronic vascular lesions, organisation with recanalisation is the typical evolution of a stable thrombus\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe process of organisation allows for partial restoration of blood flow while maintaining vessel wall integrity. The extent of recanalisation varies and depends on factors such as thrombus size, location, and time since formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Thrombi can undergo four main processes after formation: propagation, embolisation, dissolution, and organisation with recanalisation.","Organisation involves ingrowth of endothelial cells, smooth muscle cells, and fibroblasts into the thrombus, eventually forming capillary channels.","The age of a thrombus influences its potential outcomes, with older thrombi being more likely to undergo organisation than dissolution."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 4; pages 129-130."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79523"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20715"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79523"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T12:56:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T12:57:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13591"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96908"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11587"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Haemodynamic disorders: thromboembolic disease and shock","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":3,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:17:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:17:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11762"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Bleeding and clotting","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-11T17:45:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T17:45:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/ta